Trivia

Sion, the Undead Champion Sion, the Undead Champion

     
       "Who is your summoner, and what does he do?" references Kindergarten Cop.
        A side-by-side comparison can be seen here.
     
       "Get on my Chopper Chopper!" references Predator (film).
     
       "What is best in death? To crush your enemies, see them driven before you and hear the lamentation of noobs!" references Conan the Barbarian (1982 film).
        A side-by-side comparison can be seen here.

Original Sion Original Sion

     
       "So, uh, Urgot Urgot. We can't hang out anymore. I'm cool now." references his fresh relaunch. 
     
       "Even death death trembles before me." resembles  
       Veigar OriginalSquare.png "Even death trembles in my presence.".
     
       Recall.png "I'll be back." quotes The Terminator.
     
       "I feel no pain no pain!" references his old passive his old passive.
     
       "It's murdering time!" references The Thing from Fantastic Four by Marvel Comics ("It's clobbering time!")
     
       "Yes... I like this weapon this weapon... " references Heavy from Team Fortress 2.
    Sion shares quotes with:
         
          Sion OriginalCircle.png  
          Garen OriginalCircle.png  
          Kled OriginalCircle.png "Charge!"
         
          Sion OriginalCircle.png  
          Talon OriginalCircle.png  
          Trundle OriginalCircle.png "Pathetic!"

Mecha Zero Sion Mecha Zero Sion

     
       "Function is greater than form." resembles  
       Viktor OriginalSquare.png "Function over form".
     
       "Roll out - and over over!",  
       "Change shapers mecha incognito.", and  
       "Death is the right of all sentient beings." reference Transformers.
     
       "I'll be ba- un- atn- ! Sorry... I'll be back back." references The Terminator, or the Arnold Schwarzenegger accent from his pre-rework voiceover.
     
       "Peace, in my time." is a play on a quote by Ultron from Avengers: Age of Ultron ("Peace in our time") (Originally by Prime Minister Neville Chamberlain).
     
       "Robot means slave; I am robot to no one." references the real-life etymological fact that the Czecho-slovak noun robot derived from robota "drudgery, servitude".


